A black box in your car?
While U.S. road network planners struggle to find the money needed to repair declining highway infrastructure, many see a solution in the form of a small black box that attaches above your car’s dashboard.
The devices, which record all miles traveled by a motorist and transmit the information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government offices to plan to overhaul the outdated system of financing major American roads.
The generally uninteresting sector of major axis planning has suddenly provoked a lively debate and turbulent alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to push for the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you’re traveling, and possibly the road you’re on, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party has landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress can’t agree on whether to continue, several states haven’t waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to switch to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles traveled.
Thousands of motorists have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental ride.
This is truly essential for our nation.
“It’s not like we have a choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, general manager of the Southern California Association of Governments, which predicts the state will begin recording the miles traveled by every Californian motorist by 2025.
There will be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is here to do it.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country’s Highway Trust Fund, funded with taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans are no longer buying as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can travel more miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
“The gas tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed trackers on 500 cars to test a mile payment system.
“It turns out to be the most logical alternative in the long run,” he said.
Wonks calls this mileage usage fee.
It is not surprising that the idea appeals to urban liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits in ways that reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the state’s ambitious global warming laws.
But Rep. Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also considered it the most viable long-term alternative.
Reason Foundation free market supporters also appreciate the idea of getting drivers to pay miles.
“This isn’t just a tax slumping into a big black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of politics at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they get.
The movement is also backed by two former U.S. Secretaries of Transportation who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go the mile payment route.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that reportedly covered about 10,000 cars.
But the House presidency killed the proposal, addressing the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to their jobs or to the city.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to conduct the country’s most important experiment.
These motorists will soon pay the state mileage fees instead of fuel taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is trying a test on a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the east coast of the United States (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is studying how it could implement the change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their car with a device, drivers were concerned that the government could track their slightest facts and gestures.
“The concerns about Big Brother and that kind of thing are a big deal,” said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategic performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
At the start of the trial, the Nevada ACLU warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged location devices.”
There is no need to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people’s daily walks and arrivals.
Nevada is one of the few states that are now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
Research into this technology has led some state agencies to call on a small California start-up called True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to help motorists who pay taxes to states.
It sought to drill into the emerging auto insurance market, in which drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices she tested liked big-axis planners because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, uploaded periodically by modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t record their speed and track them,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are much less expensive means and much less intrusive methods of proceeding.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They can still choose not to have a device at all, preferring to pay a plan based on the average number of miles traveled by all residents of the state.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing the devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transport officials are looking to develop a charging device that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide “driving payment” insurance, and create a real-time speed data set from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Motorists would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits the system offers them,” said a paper on urban planning.
However, some transport planners wonder if the whole debate about mile payment isn't just a huge distraction.
At the San Francisco Bay Area Metropolitan Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very simply manage the Highway Trust Fund bankruptcy by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional one-off or annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and on others whose vehicles do not consume much gasoline, so that everyone pays their fair share.
“There’s no need to resort to radical surgery when you just need aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, the commission’s director of legislation and public affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
