How Biometrics Will Invade Our Lives
Finished the passwords to type to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy general manager of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person carrying out transactions in a world as transversal and transnational as the Internet.
Organizations dedicated to the protection of privacy confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but are concerned about it.
Only in 2011 and in France, the National Commission for Information Technology and Freedoms authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the shape of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most widely used biometric data are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its limitations.
“For example, some people who work with concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable,” says Philippe Robin, Technical Director of Identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And collecting as well as checking the venous network and the contour of the hand presupposes a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
It is both a security - we cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a drawback: sometimes the procedure has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted for about twenty years on other approaches, such as facial recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
By increasing the accuracy of the sensors and the computational capacity of the computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
Face recognition accuracy has increased tenfold over the past five years, says Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s R&D labs in Europe.
With our help, the UK and the Netherlands have deployed automatic border crossings using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
A unique and infallible marker, DNA also arouses hopes and concerns.
“In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data,” confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, CNIL Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC is offering law enforcement a case worth <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>90,000 to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime within an hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognize a person among others) and authentication (ensure that the person is who they claim to be).
The identification so far concerned the issuance of identity papers: biometric elements (prints, photo, iris) must be compared with the information that the state has on all citizens already registered.
This ensures that a person does not attempt to usurp someone else’s identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or store.
“We’re retrieving images from surveillance cameras and comparing them to photos of celebrities freely circulating on the Internet,” said Dany Nassif, NEC France’s head of commercial development for biometric identification solutions.
Other use: take a picture of a guy queuing in a store, track his progress thanks to facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens...) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, presence checks have been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the friend pointing for another," explains Cyrille Bataller, Accenture.
But, more and more, authentication will also affect transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing his card and putting his hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the key of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoul<0xC3><0xAA>me by Natural Security in partnership with banks and retailers: when paying in-store with his bank card, the customer does not enter his code, but inserts his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is expected to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in the box for thirty seconds less, it is appreciable," explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
And finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
“Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people’s identities are on a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure case, which crashes if you try to move it,” says Philippe Robin, of Thales.
But, in the absence of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
The specialists in the protection of privacy, they continue to worry.
“The advances in facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance,” said Andrew Patrick, Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
