Scientists have just shed light on how a dog’s tail movements are linked to his mood.
Previous studies had revealed that happy dogs moved their tail more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs moved it more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions.”
Here, we tried to see what it was like in other species.
He added that just as in humans, in dogs, the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to other dogs’ disordered tail movements, the researchers followed animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won’t be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented dogs with films featuring other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other factor of confusion – and we were able to traffic the movement of the tail and present it as going more to the left or to the right.”
When the animals saw an expressionless dog wagging the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog wagging the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail diverting mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog waving the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that dogs deliberately communicated with each other through these movements.
Instead, he thinks that dogs know from experience what movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: “If you encounter other dogs several times and if you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side results in a less friendly attitude, you will react based on that experience.”
The researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Sciences, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University discovered that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs went more easily to a robot dog when its tail was moving to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what appears in the Italian study.”
He indicated that the differences could come from the fact that the dogs that participated in the different studies did not fully consider the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
