A team of biologists led by the New York Wildlife Conservation Society has identified a new species of humpback dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, scientific mission manager at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Marine Animals and Environments (OCEAMM), returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of humpback dolphin surprise you?
That's good news, but I'm not particularly surprised.
While species have in the past been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge in the sciences of species classification.
Moreover, it is not impossible that these advances in genetics and molecular biology call into question the classification or membership of a species in a genus, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are challenged due to advances in genetics.
In the same way, two species very close morphologically have been distinguished thanks to genetics.
This is the case with the new species that has just been identified.
About a decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: the Pacific humpback dolphins and the Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyses have made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is this an important discovery as claimed by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population was already known to researchers for a long time, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only in this place.
Therefore, if a massive mortality problem caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture occurs in the region, we could be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than a local extinction of a population of a species more widespread on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered endangered or endangered based on the number of individuals on Earth, that is, the stock, and the possibility that it has to recover from neighboring stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, whose population of the newly discovered species has emerged, its stock has automatically become weaker, thus making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This blending of genes limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
The marine environment is the least well known environment.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, than to know what lives in the pit of the Marianas, only 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
We spend more money on the search for life on other planets than we do on marine research, and it’s high time that that changed.
