Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents at Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnopédies de Satie.
An evening that allows you to see all the prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and from black ink to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, also white, in the immense space that is the Maisonneuve Theatre, advances, profile, fine as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink of Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, simple trait, takes its form.
And this shape will be that of the whole room: a string of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, fully dressed in black, only hands and face uncovered, wait on either side of the playing area, rush when the next graphic appears, embody it, emerge running.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is done in solo relays, in a unison group (a mass that makes solo), in a large group of twelve solos where each performs its own sign.
One thinks of "Glory of the Morning", where, solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on posters, posed online at the front stage.
It's the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is loud, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur will take refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux's poem, monochord and monotone in the shout, and will continue dancing.
And the music to go back, and the sequence to resume.
This sonic and energetic discharge, long, if possible, ends up deafening and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are a few beautiful flashes - image creation has always been a strength at Chouinard - like those hairs that are flaking or those black fabrics that elongate the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
One has the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet the work of Michaux, has imposed herself, with her tics.
As a result, the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux’s inks, like Gestalt forms, open up a broader, more porous imagination than dance.
Only the end, in the negative, with its dancers chopped by a strobe light and the white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches magic.
The public loved it, the welcome was warm.
Gymnopedia, after intercourse, is richer.
The stage is partly draped in grey, the dancers and a piano are covered in fabrics, like furniture in a neglected house.
At the piano, dancers relay to play the scores.
Their unaddressed music, touching, give a real fragility.
On stage, couples, in duos in love, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small solos of transitions, moving ensembles, choirs, writing is less binary.
Buffons appear, also familiar to Chouinard, with a red nose, in very polarized male-female love parades.
Loves are carnal, fugitive, or player.
Gestures, laughter and small cries beautifully transpose the archaic, grace and ridicule of coitus bodies, of beings that merge.
But the play takes its real flight after salvation.
