Islamist Mohamed Morsi promised the emergence of a “new Egypt” when he took the oath of office, becoming the first freely elected president and succeeding Hosni Mubarak who was ousted 16 months earlier.
During his inauguration before the High Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamist president of the Arab world and the fifth head of state of Egypt since the overthrow of the monarchy 60 years ago.
He was sworn in before the 18 black-robed judges of the Court whose building on the banks of the Nile was built to resemble an Egyptian temple.
“We aspire to better tomorrows, a new Egypt and a second republic,” President Morsi said during the solemn ceremony broadcast live on public television.
“Today, the Egyptian people have laid the foundations for a new life – absolute freedom, true democracy and stability,” said Mr. Morsi, a 60-year-old engineer trained in the United States, from the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group considered for more than 84 years since its formation as an illegal and hard-line organization.
Hundreds of soldiers and police guarded the building when Mr. Morsi arrived shortly after 11:00 local time, followed by a small convoy.
Only a few hundred supporters had gathered before the Court to cheer for the new president, and as they stood out from the Mubarak-era presidential guise, traffic was only briefly interrupted to allow his convoy to pass through the busy streets connecting the city center to the southern suburbs.
Considered the uncharismatic “relief wheel” of the Muslim Brotherhood, his personal prestige has been greatly strengthened since his victory and Friday speech during which he tried to present himself as the candidate not only of the Islamists but of all those who want to finish the work begun during the 2011 uprising against the authoritarian Mobaruk president.
“Egypt today is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state,” said Mohamed Morsi, wearing a blue suit and a red tie, addressing the judges in the woodwork room where he was sworn in.
Later, Mr. Morsi went to the University of Cairo where he delivered his inaugural address.
He was officially greeted by a military fanfare that played the national anthem while he was on guard.
Marshal Hussein Tantaoui attended the ceremony.
Upon his arrival, he was greeted by the song “The people and the army, hand in hand...” sung by thousands of people gathered in the university’s grand amphitheatre.
Founded in 1908 and a former bastion of secular education, the University of Cairo later became a fief of Islamist student groups in the 1970s.
Morsi took a symbolic oath on Friday on Tahrir Square, from where the uprising that ended Mubarak's authoritarian regime last year began, and vowed to regain the presidential powers that the military council, which replaced the ex-president, ousted him.
But by agreeing to take an official oath before the Court, rather than before Parliament as is customary, he bows to the will of the army by showing that the struggle for power is not over.
Mr. Morsi’s speech on Tahrir Square was accompanied by spectacular populist gestures.
