John Kerry has admitted, without precedent, that American espionage “had gone too far in an inappropriate way.”
John Kerry pointed to a softening of the U.S.’s defensive attitude toward its surveillance programs by admitting, unprecedentedly, that on several occasions, espionage “had gone too far inappropriately.”
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, like Barack Obama, had ruled on “autopilot” when a series of incendiary revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about NSA espionage activities emerged.
The leaks put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Mr. Kerry said: "It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government became aware of certain things in automatic pilot mode because we had the opportunity, from the Second World War until the difficult years of the Cold War, and then of course the 11th of September."
He then became the first senior member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had crossed the line, but insisted that everyone’s rights had not been violated.
He said: “In some cases, it went too far inappropriately.”
And the President is determined to try to clarify and make clear to the people that he is now undertaking a thorough review of these practices so that no one feels wrong.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused in this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force acting for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We live in a new world where people are ready to be blown up.”
There is a radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We did prevent planes from crashing, buildings from exploding, and people from being murdered because we were able to get to know the facts in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged U.S. espionage case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counter-terrorism efforts with the United States, the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he had spoken before members of the European Parliament and others this week and that he was concerned about the threats they had uttered about a possible withdrawal of anti-terrorist organizations due to the feeling of frustration with the National Security Agency's surveillance.
“It is really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans remain on our side in our mutual commitment to the fight against terrorism,” Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term, and chairman of the U.S. Senate’s European Affairs Subcommittee, said in an interview from Washington.
And I’m going to go to Europe to make them understand that we have to continue working together to fight terrorism, despite the anger caused by the NSA programs.
The press reports that the NSA has captured millions of communications in Europe, which has damaged relations with some U.S. allies, but the director of the agency said this week that it was inaccurate and that it was a misunderstanding as it concerned metadata that the NATO allies had collected.
Other revelations reported documents released by Snowden that the NSA had intercepted data and communications from the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and those of 34 other heads of state.
The Director of Intelligence, James Clapper, justified the espionage of the Allies by stating that it was necessary and that it was a common practice on both sides.
In this tumultuous atmosphere, Murphy indicated that his office was organizing a trip from Congress, which is due to take place this year, and that he hoped the delegation would include members of both parties and both chambers.
The names of the other participating legislators are expected to be revealed in the coming days.
He indicated that the itinerary remained to be defined.
Murphy said the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show “affectionate firmness.”
He explained that European heads of state should be honest with their citizens about the type of spying programs they have been implementing themselves for years.
“We can modify our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they also need to understand that we are not the only ones in the world to spy,” Murphy said.
